  /* Section 1–2: Contesto */
  'arg.s1.label': 'Sections 1 — 2',
  'arg.s1.title': 'The macroeconomic legacy',
  'arg.s1.p1': "Argentina's problems did not emerge recently, nor can they be attributed to a single government. From 2009 to 2023, the country ran continuous budget deficits, with the deficit/GDP ratio persistently exceeding 3% from 2012 onwards. Public debt, which had fallen to 40% of GDP in 2011, peaked at 155% by end 2023.",
  'arg.s1.p2': "The mechanism that brought Argentina to critical economic conditions was debt monetization. The Central Bank, devoid of genuine independence, financed the deficit by printing new money, fueling a deficit-money-inflation spiral for decades. By end 2023, annual inflation had reached 211%, net reserves were negative and the country stood on the brink of default.",
  'arg.s1.p3': "The Fernández government (2019–2023) represented the peak of this crisis: a fiscal deficit exceeding 5% of GDP, an additional quasi-fiscal deficit of 10% through the Leliq instruments, and public debt at 155%. It is in this context that the Milei government intervened, launching a program based on shock therapy to restore public finances.",

  'arg.s1.acc1.btn': 'Explore the historical context',
  'arg.s1.acc1.body': `
    <p>First the government of Néstor Kirchner (2003–2007), then that of Cristina Fernández (2007–2015), fueled the deficit–debt–inflation spiral, which, together with export taxes on the agri-food sector and the introduction of the exchange rate freeze (cepo cambiario) in 2011, made the country's economic model and recovery unsustainable.</p>
    <p>Subsequently, the Macri government (2015–2019) attempted to stabilize the economy and halt the financial crisis, signing a record agreement with the IMF for $57 billion. The financing was granted with the aim of reducing the fiscal deficit, but the program failed to meet its objectives, further worsening the economic crisis: the peso depreciated rapidly in 2018, making dollar-denominated debt unsustainable and forcing further monetary issuance.</p>
    <p>The situation deteriorated under the Fernández government (2019–2023), which issued over $100 billion in peso-denominated bonds financed by the Central Bank, further widening the deficit. In addition to accumulating a fiscal deficit exceeding 5% of GDP, the Fernández government generated an additional estimated deficit of 10% of GDP through the Central Bank, which issued short-term high-yield instruments — the Leliq — to sterilize excess liquidity. This contributed to an unsustainable accumulation of public debt, which at the time of Milei's inauguration represented one of the principal challenges to address.</p>`,

  'arg.s1.acc2.btn': 'Key concept: the debt monetization mechanism',
  'arg.s1.acc2.body': `
    <p>The Argentine Central Bank, lacking genuine independence, has historically been subordinate to political power. This allowed the government to pursue a policy of debt monetization — financing the fiscal deficit and public debt through the issuance of new currency, with the Central Bank subsequently purchasing government bonds.</p>
    <p>This practice has become illegal in Europe, not only because it encourages the government to be careless with its public finances, but above all because it is an inherently inflationary policy. Filling the deficit by printing new money year after year is the perfect recipe for rising, out-of-control inflation.</p>
    <p>With high and rising inflation, real wages and citizens' purchasing power erode even before they have the chance to grow. The erosion of real wages pushes citizens to put greater pressure on the government, demanding more intervention and assistance, which in turn leads to larger deficits, new money, and new inflation.</p>`,

  'arg.s1.acc3.btn': 'Key concept: the exchange rate freeze (cepo cambiario)',
  'arg.s1.acc3.body': `
    <p>The cepo cambiario consists of a series of restrictions imposed by the Central Bank on the purchase of foreign currency — particularly US dollars — and on capital movements. Its purpose is to curb capital flight and protect the Central Bank's reserves. However, this instrument introduced a series of distortions arising from the emergence of parallel exchange rates.</p>
    <p>The government sets an official exchange rate, while informal rates simultaneously emerge — most notably the "dólar blue" — which incentivize economic actors to exploit the arbitrage between rates. The differential between the official and parallel rates reached 170% by end 2023, creating arbitrage incentives and distorting relative prices across the economy, with negative effects on exports and on the allocative efficiency of the productive system.</p>`,

  /* Timeline */
  'arg.tl.y1': '2003 – 2015',
  'arg.tl.t1': 'Kirchner governments: expansion of public spending, exchange controls since 2011, deficit–debt–inflation spiral. The differential between official and parallel exchange rates reached 170% by end 2023.',
  'arg.tl.y2': '2015 – 2019',
  'arg.tl.t2': 'Macri government: IMF agreement worth $57 billion — the largest in Fund history. The program missed its targets. The peso depreciated sharply in 2018.',
  'arg.tl.y3': '2019 – 2023',
