  'arg.s4.bars2.n6':      'Social security benefits',
  'arg.s4.bars2.note':    'Source: Argentine government budgets — Ministry of Economy. Real changes deflated by CPI.',

  /* Section 5: Monetaria */
  'arg.s5.label': 'Section 5',
  'arg.s5.title': 'Monetary and exchange rate policy',
  'arg.s5.p1': "The most significant macroeconomic result of the program is disinflation. Monthly inflation fell from 25.5% in December 2023 to 2.7% in December 2024, a reduction of more than 20 percentage points in the first 5 months; annual inflation fell from 211% in 2023 to 117% in 2024. The crawling peg, setting a predetermined monthly devaluation rate (initially at 2%, then 1%), functioned as a nominal anchor. The system was subsequently replaced by exchange rate bands, allowing a reduction in the real appreciation of the peso. Additionally, the Leliq instruments introduced under the Fernández government were significantly reduced in favor of longer-term instruments.",
  'arg.s5.p2': "These results must be qualified, as the decline in annual inflation partly reflects a statistical base effect. The most reliable indicator is monthly inflation, which shows a genuine downward trend. Monetary policies have been successful, but structural risks persist: wage pressures from collective renegotiations, tariff shocks from subsidy elimination, and exchange rate pressures toward the upper band limit.",

  'arg.s5.acc1.btn': 'Deep dive: instruments, results and residual risks',
  'arg.s5.acc1.body': `
    <p>With the elimination of the cepo, the crawling peg was replaced by exchange rate bands, giving the peso greater ability to adapt to market prices. This system allows the currency to float freely within the bands, with Central Bank intervention if it approaches the limits — buying or selling dollars. The established range is between 1,000 and 1,400 pesos per dollar, with a monthly adjustment initially set at 1%, then indexed to the previous month's inflation from January 2026. This approach reduces the real appreciation of the peso and facilitates reserve accumulation — one of the most significant unresolved challenges facing the current administration.</p>
    <p>Overall, monetary policies have been successful, but have not entirely eliminated the risk of an inflation rebound. With the deceleration of inflation, collective wage agreements have begun to produce nominal increases above current inflation, initiating a recovery in real wages — previously eroded by inflation peaks. However, this also represents a risk: if wage negotiations require significant nominal increases, it can lead to a wage-price spiral.</p>
    <p>Rising nominal wages represent higher costs for firms, which tend to pass these costs on to final prices, fueling inflation. Second, the public spending cuts also affected subsidies. This may lead to price increases in services such as energy and transport — which are often subsidized — and has therefore direct effects on consumer prices, feeding inflation. This occurs because, while the subsidy keeps prices low in the short term, its sudden elimination creates a supply shock with immediate inflationary effects. A third risk is of an exchange rate nature: potential pressures on the exchange rate toward the upper band limit could transmit new inflationary impulses through the import channel.</p>
    <p>The disinflation process is documented and solid in its trajectory, but remains exposed to structural rebound risks, requiring constant monitoring. The decision not to proceed with full dollarization has preserved the Central Bank and its monetary policy instruments, which proved central to the stabilization process.</p>`,

  'arg.s5.acc2.btn': 'Key concept: what are the Leliq',
  'arg.s5.acc2.body': `
    <p>The Leliq (Letras de Liquidez) are short-term debt instruments issued by the Argentine Central Bank, placed primarily with commercial banks. They were created as a sterilization tool: when the Central Bank wishes to reduce liquidity in circulation — for example, because it has printed too much money — it issues these instruments and sells them to banks, withdrawing pesos from the system.</p>
    <p>The problem is that the Leliq pay high interest rates. In the context of high inflation and negative real rates that characterized Argentina, the yields offered to make the instruments attractive to banks were very high, and the accrued interest was itself paid by issuing new money or new instruments — a self-reinforcing cycle. At the time of Milei's inauguration, the Leliq stock was worth approximately 10% of GDP, with nominal interest rates exceeding 100% annually.</p>
    <p>Milei progressively dismantled this mechanism, replacing the Leliq with longer-term instruments and reducing the overall stock. The objective was to eliminate the inflationary pressure generated by the interest payments and return the Central Bank to a more manageable balance sheet — a prerequisite for re-establishing institutional credibility.</p>`,

  'arg.s5.acc3.btn': 'Key concept: the statistical base effect',
  'arg.s5.acc3.body': `
    <p>Annual inflation is calculated by comparing the price level of a given month with that of the same month in the previous year. When the comparison period — the denominator — is a year in which prices were already very high, the annual rate tends to fall automatically, even if prices continue to rise in the current period.</p>
    <p>In the Argentine case, this effect is particularly significant. 2023 was a year of exceptional inflation, with monthly peaks exceeding 12% from August onwards and a December at 25.5%. Comparing the months of 2024 against this very high base produces artificially compressed annual rates, which may give the impression of a faster disinflation than is actually occurring.</p>
    <p>This is why monthly inflation is the most accurate indicator for assessing the current pace of the process. It is not affected by the base effect and directly shows how much prices are rising at any given moment. That said, the results achieved are significant. Monthly inflation had not fallen below 3% since August 2021, and annual inflation had not been below 33% since July 2018.</p>`,

