  /* Section 6: Debito */
  'arg.s6.label': 'Section 6',
  'arg.s6.title': 'Public debt, IMF and international relations',
  'arg.s6.p1': "The debt/GDP ratio fell from 155% in 2023 to 83% in 2024 — an apparently extraordinary drop that nonetheless requires deeper analysis. The debt itself has not diminished: it is the nominal GDP in pesos that grew rapidly due to inflation, while the foreign currency-denominated debt followed a slower pace. Real GDP in 2024 contracted. The denominator exploded, the numerator did not, and the ratio declined accordingly.",
  'arg.s6.p2': "External liquidity is the central issue of this section. The 2025 IMF agreement — worth $20 billion in total, with $12 billion disbursed immediately — enabled a partial reconstruction of gross reserves. Added to this are a $20 billion credit line from the US Treasury and the renewal of the $5 billion swap line with China. These agreements contributed to reserve reconstruction, but the process is still ongoing, as net reserves remain fragile relative to the approximately $15 billion in maturities due in 2026.",

  'arg.s6.acc1.btn': 'Deep dive: IMF agreements, geopolitical triangulation and sustainability',
  'arg.s6.acc1.body': `
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">IMF agreements</strong><br>
    After the 2001 default and the early repayment in 2005, Argentina operated for over a decade without active programs with the IMF, given the country's instability. However, from 2018 onwards, the IMF and Argentina signed three agreements.</p>
    <p>The first, in 2018, provided for a record agreement of approximately $50 billion, later expanded to $57 billion — the largest in IMF history. The agreement aimed to stabilize the Argentine economy and reduce inflation and the fiscal deficit. The program failed to meet its objectives; economic stabilization did not consolidate, converting private-sector debt into debt toward the Fund and contributing to worsening the conditions inherited by the subsequent government.</p>
    <p>The second agreement was signed in 2022, constituting a debt restructuring and providing for economic policies to strengthen economic stability, reduce inflation and increase Central Bank reserves.</p>
    <p>In 2025, a new agreement was reached, providing $20 billion in total financing, with the primary objective of restoring Central Bank reserves. Among the IMF's requirements: continuation of fiscal deficit elimination, removal of exchange controls and inflation control. In July 2025, the IMF approved the first review of the new support program, unlocking a further $2 billion. The funds disbursed upfront reflect the urgent need to rebuild reserves and signal the Fund's confidence in the program to the markets. The Fund approved the review despite the failure to meet reserve targets, partly thanks to progress on the fiscal front.</p>
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">Argentina between the US and China</strong><br>
    In addition to the funds obtained through the IMF, Argentina also signed swap agreements with China and the United States. The Trump administration pledged support to Argentina, signing a $20 billion agreement through a US Treasury credit line to intervene in currency markets and stabilize the Argentine peso.</p>
    <p>The agreement signed in late October 2025 strengthened investor confidence — with the United States as lender of last resort — but also geopolitically aligned Argentina with Washington for the coming years. The plan serves to consolidate US influence in the South American region, positioning itself as a credible alternative to other international actors, such as China.</p>
    <p>Relations with China had appeared to break down at end 2023, after Beijing froze the swap line following Milei's criticisms of the Chinese government. Nonetheless, to avoid default and stabilize the currency, Milei renewed the swap line — approximately $5 billion — confirming China as an essential partner for trade liquidity and investment in strategic sectors. This reflects the pragmatism of the Milei government: despite ideological differences and the possibility of turning to other countries such as the US, China remains an important trade partner.</p>
    <p>Argentina thus finds itself in a position of balance between the two countries, while also being the object of strategic competition between the two superpowers, with the US attempting to re-establish its presence and displace that of China.</p>
    <p>Despite the trade surplus, the situation remains critical, as net reserves remain scarce and the country faces the risk of new currency crises. The reconstruction of foreign exchange stocks is a slow process: the persistent scarcity of foreign currency limits the capacity to meet international obligations, maintaining high pressure on the exchange rate.</p>
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">Debt sustainability</strong><br>
    Medium-to-long-term debt sustainability derives from Argentina's capacity to pay interest — amounting to approximately $15 billion for 2026, of which $4 billion to the IMF. The current planning has in effect deferred debt maturities to the medium term, reducing immediate pressure but not eliminating the risk.</p>
    <p>The new financing from the IMF and credit agreements with China and the US increase immediate liquidity, but simultaneously increase the weight of future contractual obligations. The reserves therefore remain the critical point: the Milei government is attempting to rebuild them, but the process remains vulnerable to external shocks and exchange rate volatility.</p>`,

  'arg.s6.acc2.btn': 'Key concept: why the debt/GDP ratio can be misleading',
  'arg.s6.acc2.body': `
    <p>Argentine debt is largely denominated in US dollars, so its value in pesos increases when the peso depreciates. During 2024 and 2025, the government maintained a controlled depreciation regime — the peso depreciated nominally through the crawling peg, but at a rate lower than domestic inflation, producing real appreciation.</p>
    <p>The denominator — nominal GDP in pesos — increased rapidly due to inflation, while the numerator — the debt — increased more slowly, producing a contraction in the ratio. Overall, therefore, the ratio declined not because the debt decreased, but because the nominal value of the economy grew faster than the debt did; indeed, real GDP contracted in 2024.</p>
    <p>To assess sustainability, one must therefore analyze debt in absolute terms, its currency composition and the maturity schedule over time, as well as the country's capacity to generate foreign currency to meet its obligations. The IMF projections are nonetheless positive, indicating a decline in debt to 78.7% in 2025, 73% in 2026, with a gradual reduction to 58% by 2030.</p>`,

