  /* Section 7: Sociale */
  'arg.s7.label': 'Section 7',
  'arg.s7.title': 'Social impact: poverty, wages and the labour market',
  'arg.s7.p1': "The poverty trajectory describes a V-shape: from 41.7% in the second half of 2023 to a peak of 52.9% in the first half of 2024, down to 28.2% in the second half of 2025. The peak is directly attributable to the December 2023 devaluation, which eroded real purchasing power before wages could adjust. The recovery followed with the deceleration of inflation and subsequent collective wage renegotiations.",
  'arg.s7.p2': "The labour market, however, tells a more complex story. The employment rate remained stable at around 48.5%, yet the Argentine market is characterized by high labour informality: INDEC estimates that approximately 43% of the working population is informally employed. Real wages followed the poverty V-curve, with a gradual recovery to pre-crisis levels in early 2025.",
  'arg.s7.p3': "While the formal private sector benefited from paritarias (collective wage negotiations), public sector workers and informal workers did not have access to this mechanism — the former due to public spending cuts, the latter due to the absence of contractual protections. As a result, the cost of economic adjustment fell asymmetrically on the population.",

  'arg.s7.acc1.btn': 'Deep dive: poverty, real wages and the asymmetric costs of adjustment',
  'arg.s7.acc1.body': `
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">Poverty and indigence indices</strong><br>
    INDEC data have semi-annual frequency and are based on a 2004/2005 expenditure structure, which implies that the goods carrying the greatest weight in the index reflect consumption patterns from twenty years ago. In a high-inflation context, this can distort the measurement of the poverty threshold relative to the actual spending structure of households. This is why these data are often compared with the UCA-ODSA, which publishes quarterly data and uses a more updated structure, yielding higher poverty rates but enabling better analysis of short-term dynamics.</p>
    <p>It should be noted that the poverty index measures the percentage of households and individuals whose income is insufficient to cover a basket of essential goods and services — not just food. Quarterly data analysis reveals that the peak occurred only in the first quarter of 2024, with a decline beginning as early as the second quarter. The cause of this increase is attributable to the December 2023 peso devaluation: the devaluation led to a rise in the real prices of goods in general, including basic necessities.</p>
    <p>The rapid decline within a semester is instead due to the strong disinflation, which — with consequent wage adjustments — enabled a recovery in the population's purchasing power. Analyzing indigence — those unable to cover even basic food needs with their income — the dynamics are similar, with a peak in the first half of 2024 and a rapid decline in the second half, falling from 18.1% to 6.9%.</p>
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">Real wages</strong><br>
    Real wages experienced the devaluation and elevated inflation — mirroring the poverty V-curve — with a consequent loss of purchasing power until the first quarter of 2024, followed by a gradual recovery that brought real wages back to pre-crisis levels in early 2025. It is not yet possible to establish the net effect of Milei's policies on real wages, as they have only just recovered the losses accumulated during shock therapy.</p>
    <p>The public sector saw the greatest wage decline, both nominal and real. The public and informal sectors are those that suffer most from inflationary shocks — the former due to contractual rigidity and fiscal policy dependence, the latter for the exact opposite reason: the absence of contractual protections. In a context of inflation containment and fiscal deficit reduction, public spending cuts translated into wage increases below inflation, with consequent real losses.</p>
    <p>The informal sector has no indexation mechanism: informal workers, lacking collective contracts, have no social security coverage, and their wages depend entirely on individual bargaining with the local market. In high-inflation environments, their incomes grow much more slowly.</p>
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">The cost of adjustment</strong><br>
    The cost of fiscal consolidation and inflation reduction fell asymmetrically on employed workers, and in particular on the informal economy. The private sector demonstrated greater adaptability thanks to the paritarias mechanism — collective wage negotiations that allowed nominal increases above inflation during 2024.</p>
    <p>Informal workers were unable to benefit from this instrument, which influenced the poverty V-curve discussed above. Structural problems remain: the labour market is largely informal. This segment of the population is exposed to shocks without buffers; public sector workers are also subject to spending cuts.</p>
    <p>To this must be added that the data collected by INDEC through the EPH surveys cover approximately 70% of the population — those in urban contexts. This means that the data likely underestimate informal wage dynamics, as well as the average national standard of living and the true extent of poverty.</p>
    <p>Finally, the loss of real wages does not disappear with their recovery: those who had to cut consumption and investment do not automatically return to their starting point. This phenomenon is known in the literature as the "scarring effect," describing the permanent marks that prolonged shocks leave on human capital and expectations. It is a significant effect, because Argentina has accumulated many cycles of this kind: the data do not capture the persistence of individual costs, which remain asymmetrically distributed — particularly between those who had protective mechanisms and those who did not.</p>`,

  'arg.s7.acc2.btn': 'Key concept: why informality distorts statistics',
  'arg.s7.acc2.body': `
    <p>Informal labour creates distortions on several fronts. First, the definition of unemployment follows the standard used in most countries: a person is unemployed if they are not working but are actively seeking employment. This implies that if a person has performed any informal work activity, they are classified as employed, which means people in precarious situations are counted as occupied, artificially lowering the unemployment rate.</p>
    <p>The second effect concerns wages. Those without a contract do not appear in formal wage statistics, receive no social safety nets and, if they lose their job, do not enter unemployment statistics — they simply exit the labour force. This means that official wage dynamics over-represent the formal sector, which is also the one with greater bargaining power and access to paritarias.</p>
    <p>The third effect is fiscal: informal workers do not contribute to social security revenues, reducing the resources available to the state and concentrating the tax burden on a narrower base. In a country with 43% informality, any statistic on employment, wages and poverty must be read through this filter — official data accurately describe the formal sector, but only partially capture the real country.</p>`,

