  /* Section 8: Rating */
  'arg.s8.label': 'Section 8',
  'arg.s8.title': 'Sovereign rating, country risk and return to markets',
  'arg.s8.p1': "The improvement in macroeconomic conditions has also been recorded by financial markets. The EMBI — the spread between Argentine sovereign bonds and US Treasuries, an indicator of investor-perceived risk — fell from 1,964 basis points in January 2024 to 561 basis points in December 2025, with an intermediate peak in September 2025 (1,222 bp) signaling that investor confidence is not yet consolidated. All three major rating agencies carried out upgrades, while keeping Argentina in deep speculative territory: the risk of default is not yet considered negligible.",
  'arg.s8.p2': "At end 2025, Argentina returned to international markets with the issuance of the Bonar 2029N: $1 billion in total, a 6.5% coupon, issued at 91 cents on the dollar. Demand exceeded supply by 42%, signaling investor interest above expectations. This is a significant step for a country that had been effectively excluded from international markets since the 2020 default.",

  'arg.s8.acc1.btn': 'Deep dive: EMBI, rating agencies and market access',
  'arg.s8.acc1.body': `
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">EMBI</strong><br>
    The EMBI (Emerging Markets Bond Index) measures the yield differential between the sovereign bonds of an emerging country and US Treasury bonds, considered the risk-free benchmark. This spread, expressed in basis points — where 100 bp equals 1% — represents the premium investors require to hold Argentine debt instead of US debt. The higher the spread, the higher the perceived risk and the more expensive it is for the country to borrow on international markets. In January 2024, the spread was 1,964 bp: Argentina was paying approximately 19% more than the US to raise capital.</p>
    <p>The decline to 561 bp in December 2025 is significant, but must be contextualized. The volatility along the path was elevated: the September 2025 peak at 1,222 bp signals that investor confidence is not linear and that markets continue to price in residual structural vulnerabilities. The current level places Argentina in the high-spread range among emerging markets: countries such as Brazil typically trade below 200 bp, and investment grade begins around 150 bp. The improvement is real, but the distance from full normalization remains wide.</p>
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">Rating agencies</strong><br>
    On the ratings front, all three major agencies — S&P, Moody's and Fitch — carried out upgrades during 2024–2025, but absolute levels remain low. CCC+ for S&P and Fitch, Caa1 for Moody's: all classifications in deep speculative territory, signaling substantial vulnerability and dependence on favorable conditions to meet obligations. Investment grade — the threshold that opens access to institutional investors with conservative mandates — is still distant and would require a multi-year stabilization path without discontinuity.</p>
    <p><strong style="color: var(--text); font-weight: 500;">Bonar 2029N</strong><br>
    The Bonar 2029N represents the first concrete test of the return to markets. A 42% oversubscription is a positive signal, but the issue price at 91 cents — i.e., below par — indicates that the market still prices a non-negligible residual risk. Investors have returned, but with an explicit risk premium embedded in the price.</p>`,

